com.ekuefler.supereventbus.priority
Annotation Type WithPriority

@Documented
@Inherited
@Target(value=METHOD)
public @interface WithPriority

Defines the priority of a handler method annotated with Subscribe. Handlers with a higher priority are always invoked before handlers with a lower priority. The order in which handlers of the same priority are invoked is undefined. If a priority is not specified with this annotation, it will be given a priority of zero. For example, defining the following three handlers and posting MyEvent would cause the alters "three", "two", and "one" to be shown, in that order: 

 @Subscribe @WithPriority(-1)
 void after(MyEvent event) {
   Window.alert("one");
 }

 @Subscribe
 void normal(MyEvent event) {
   Window.alert("two");
 }

 @Subscribe @WithPriority(1)
 void before(MyEvent event) {
   Window.alert("three");
 }
In general it is best to minimize usage of this annotation such that each handler can operate independently of other handlers. Priorities should only be set for handlers that must explicitly run before or after the majority of handlers, such as loggers that record when events start and finish being processed.

ekuefler@gmail.com (Erik Kuefler)

 int value
          The priority to use for this handler.
 

Element Detail

value

public abstract int value
The priority to use for this handler. Higher-priority events are always handled before lower-priority events, with the default priority being 0. Note that priorities may be negative to force handlers to be run after other handlers.
